Average value of the total spendings on the courses are $562.3128 dollars.

mean(data2$Total.spend)
## [1] 562.3128

In order to be able to include the spendings in the analysis I converted the spendings into factor variable in the following way: customers who paid less than $562,3128 were encoded as 0, and people who paid more than the average value were encoded as 1.

data2$Total.spend<-ifelse(data2$Total.spend<562.3128,0,1)

I have excluded from the dataset the first variable which is ID.Also, I have excluded the variable Number of courses as I think that it is the result after choosing courses.

data2<-data2[,-1]
data2<-data2[,-14]
data<-as.matrix(data2)
txn<-as(data, "transactions")
itemFrequencyPlot(txn[,(17:34)])

As we can see from the frequency chart, the most 3 demanded corses are “Introduction to SPSS”,“Introduction to SPSS and Statistics”, “Fast Track”.

First, I have run rules only for courses to understand which courses are chosen with others.

Education centers based on this information can suggest different course packages for different customers based on the question how much they are ready to pay(above or below the average).
